{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "% BARPA driver demo\n",
    "\n",
    "BARPA (Bureau of Meteorology Atmospheric Regional Projections for Australia) is a dataset made of regional downscaling of CMIP6 historical and climate projection runs for the Australia/New Zealand region at a resolution around 17 km.\n",
    "More information can be found on the NCI page to the dataset: https://opus.nci.org.au/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=264241161\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset focuses and atmosphere only. It has historical runs as well as runs for 3 climate projection scenarios (SSP126, SSP370 and SSP585). Except for the SSP585 scenario for which only 2 realisations are available, 7 realisations are available for all other scenarios with each realisation being forced by different models (source_id in CMIP6 vocabulary).\n",
    "\n",
    "The data is available only as variables in 2 dimensions of spaces (sometimes multiple variables are available corresponding to different levels). The data is available for different time resolutions ranging from hourly to monthly. The data is published by the Australian Bureau of Meteorology under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license and accessible via a thredds server.\n",
    "\n",
    "The data is accessible for convenience in datamesh as virtual datacubes. Each datacube is defined for a single scenario and time resolution and contains all variables and sources/members available on the thredds server.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook illustrates interactions with the datacubes via the datamesh python interface.\n",
    "\n",
    "NB:\n",
    "- IMPORTANT: 2 calendars (with and without leap days) are used accross the different model runs. In order to fit all models in the same datacubes, we had to align them all to a single calendar including leap days. Hence some of the models will have no data (nans) for all leap days. Depending on your use case, you might what to remove/account for those nans when using the data.\n",
    "- We encourage users to favour the query interface to access the data as the datacubes are large and this will make for a much better user experience.\n",
    "- Datasets can be spatially subsampled using a bounding box filter or point interpolation but we know that at present polygon based filtering is not working\n",
    "- It is likely the datacubes can still be optimised and any feedback/bug report is welcome."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's get started with the demo and as always start by loading the necessary libraries."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import os, dotenv\n",
    "from oceanum.datamesh import Connector, Query\n",
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "dotenv.load_dotenv(\"/home/sebastien/.env/.datamesh\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# For now the BARPA data is only available  on the Oceanum development platform so we point \n",
    "# the connector to the development server.\n",
    "datamesh = Connector(service=\"https://datamesh.oceanum.tech\",\n",
    "                     token=os.getenv(\"OCEANUM_USER_IO_TOKEN\"))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here is a list of the available BARPA datasets. The id is self explanatory but it is always possible\n",
    "do a get_datasource to get more information."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {

       " 'bom_barpa_ssp126_1hr',\n",
       " 'bom_barpa_ssp370_1hr',\n",

    "# Monthly data\n",
    "\n",
    "There is nothing special about accessing the monthly data but for illustration purposes (and to make sure the datacubes work), we will access the montly data interpolated at a single point location.\n",
    "Let's start with the historical data for which we only ask for suface temperature data for one of the ensemble members."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {

    "                             ), use_dask=True)\n",

   ]

   "source": [
    "# Calendars and NAN data \n",
    "\n",
    "As explained in the introduction, 2 calendars (with and without leap days) are used accross the different model runs. In order to fit all models in the same datacubes, we had to align them all to a single calendar including leap days. Hence some of the models will have no data (nans) for all leap days. Depending on your use case, you might what to remove/account for those nans when using the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we give a  quick illustration of the issue by downloading hourly surface temparature data interpolated at a single point location for the time period range from the 27th of February to the the 2nd of March 2020 (which is a leap year)."
   ]
  },
  {
